          .row
            .col-lg-10.col-lg-offset-1.col-md-10.col-md-offset-1.col-sm-12.col-xs-12
              p
                | The Constitution of Ireland has a number of articles that are relevant to the law on education. Article 42 of the Constitution deals with education. Other articles also have a bearing on education law, in particular the articles dealing with the family and religion (Articles 41 and 44).
                br
                br
                |            
                b Minimum education
                |            
                br
                |            The Education (Welfare) Act 2000 does not give a definition of a &ldquo;minimum education&rdquo;. However, it does provide that the Minister may set out a &ldquo;prescribed minimum education&rdquo;. That minimum standard may be different for children of different ages and of different capacities &ndash; including physical, mental and emotional capacities.
                |            The Act also provides that children educated outside the mainstream school system are to be identified and assessed in order to ensure that the education they are receiving meets the minimum standards. The register is maintained by the National Education Welfare Board.
                |            
                br
                br
                |            
                b Free primary education
                |            
                br
                |            In the Sinnott case, the Supreme Court decided that the right to free primary education ends at age 18 and does not continue on the basis of need.
